  "translations": {
    "en": {
      "description": {
        "text": "From Gothenburg, take Route 40 towards Borås. Turn off towards Hyssna onto Route 156. At Hyssna, turn left towards Bollebygd/Seglora, then take a minor road to Seglora (approx. 10 km).\n\nFrom Borås, take the old Varberg road towards Viskafors. After Seglora Church, turn right towards Hyssna. The old crag appears on the right.",
        "method": "llm",
        "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
        "sourceIds": [
          "legacy:seglora-gamla"
        ]
      },
      "sections": {
        "introduktion": {
          "title": {
            "text": "Introduction",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:seglora-gamla"
            ]
          },
          "body": {
            "text": "The Old Crag has bolted, trad and mixed routes. The climbing here is different in character, with routes of more varied lengths. The rock is less featured, but has more formations that make for different climbing compared with the New Crag. Grades are tougher at the Old Crag than at the new one.\n\nThe crag faces south or south-east and gets the sun until around three. The Old Crag stands in open farmland but is shaded by some trees. It is close to the road and parking. The landowner has provided a car park and charges a climbing fee of SEK 20 per person per day. After prolonged rain, the crag is slow to dry as water runs down from the mossy ground above. In spring 2004 it was not properly dry until the end of March.",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:seglora-gamla"
            ]
          }
        },
        "historia": {
          "title": {
            "text": "History",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:seglora-gamla"
            ]
          },
          "body": {
            "text": "The Old Crag, or Ljungsslättsberget as the locals call it, is a fairly steep crag in places, with numerous roofs and aretes. The rock is very solid with good friction, and the holds are generally finger-friendly. The crag was discovered in 1988 by Mikael Wegrelius, a recently arrived Stockholmer looking for a suitable place to practise climbing. Together with his wife Lena and a few others, Mikael quickly put up around 25 routes. Most of these were pure nut-protected routes, such as Gåsamarsch, grade 6b (6).\n\n1991 was a major year in the crag’s history. The local climbers had discovered the meaning of life – sport climbing. New routes equipped with shiny bolts and abseil anchors were put up at a furious pace. Several excellent but rarely climbed nut-protected routes were also bolted. One of these is the great classic Ankdammen (grade 6c+), which had probably seen fewer than five ascents before it was bolted.\n\nToday there are around 60 routes on the crag, almost 30 of which are high-quality pure sport routes. Most of the sport routes are in the 6a+–7a range, with only a handful in the harder grades. The potential for new routes at the crag must be considered low, although perhaps another six to eight routes could be bolted. During the spring, however, the Mark climbers will focus primarily on converting a number of the much-hated ‘mixed’ routes into pure sport routes.\n\nIn spring 1996, a conflict arose between the landowner and climbers.\n\nThe crag faces south, with sun until around 16:00, and is relatively exposed to the wind, so it can be rather chilly in early spring and late autumn. The steeper routes are usually perfectly climbable even when it rains.",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:seglora-gamla"
            ]
          }
        },
        "vagbeskrivning": {
          "title": {
            "text": "Directions",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:seglora-gamla"
            ]
          },
          "body": {
            "text": "From Gothenburg, take road 40 towards Borås. Turn off towards Hyssna onto road 156. At Hyssna, turn left towards Bollebygd/Seglora, then take a smaller road to Seglora (about 10 km).\n\nFrom Borås, take the old Varberg road towards Viskafors. After Seglora church, turn right towards Hyssna. The Old Crag appears on the right.",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:seglora-gamla"
            ]
          }
        },
        "access": {
          "title": {
            "text": "Access",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:seglora-gamla"
            ]
          },
          "body": {
            "text": "The landowner has provided a car park and charges a parking fee of SEK 20 per person per day. In spring 1996, a conflict arose between the landowner and climbers because of all the constant traffic across his land. This was resolved by introducing the parking fee.",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:seglora-gamla"
            ]
          }
        },
